<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-12T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-12T06:00:00-05:00" n="724" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d724">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/142: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gwynn</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-12T13:00:00+02:00">August 12,
                                    1942—1 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received August 13—3:19 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>281. Reference paragraph 2 of my 280.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Monsieur Baelen, Catroux’s Chef du Cabinet Politique told me that
                                a letter has just been received from Casey urging the necessity of
                                holding elections in the immediate future in Syria and Lebanon and
                                that Casey had said the United States Government had indicated that
                                it too desired these elections. I asked Baelen if he could give me a
                                verbatim extract of Casey’s letter. He said that he would have to
                                ask Catroux’s permission but thought it would not be refused. I will
                                wire it immediately if obtainable.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>In view of the ideas I have expressed, I should greatly appreciate
                                being informed if there is any basis of truth in Casey’s reported
                                statement.</item>
                            <label>3.</label>
                            <item>If elections should be held, I think it a foregone conclusion that
                                they will be not only anti-French but anti-Ally unless they are very
                                actively manipulated.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gwynn</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>